onds to the particular status of the archive "after Auschwitz." What remains in this late phase of memory culture is the post-Holocaust archive, which at once ensures and hauntsthe future of Holocaust memory. Drawing on the thinking of Freud, Derrida, and Georges Didi-Huberman, this book traces the political, ethical, and aesthetic implications of the archival turn in contemporary German memory culture across different media and genres. In its discussion of recent memorials, documentary film and theater, as well as prose narratives, all of which engage with the material legacy of the Nazi past, it argues that the performanceof "archive work" is not only crucial to contemporary memory work but also fundamentally challenges it. Dora Osborne is Senior Lecturer in German at the University of St Andrews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)-Germany-Public opinion. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aBerlin Republic.  aDerrida.  aDora Osborne.  aFreud.  aGeorges Didi-Huberman.  aGerman Memory Culture.  aGerman history.  aHolocaust.  aNational Socialism.  aPost-Holocaust Archive.  aaesthetic implications.  aarchival turn.  acontemporary German memory.  aethical implications.  amaterial legacy.  amemory culture.  amemory work.  apolitical implications.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446649?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446649/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles